I would suggest you to use some tag instead of `##` - for example `span`. Then you can use `find()` function to find your elements.

------
## Exmaple
If you can&#39;t modify original text than you can use `replace()` function with regular expression to replace `##` with for example `span` and then apply styles for each `span` of your element.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;
    // your element in string
    var myvar = &#39;&lt;p&gt;Hi, ##CandidateName## and this is your ##CandidateEmail##&lt;/p&gt;&#39;;

    // replace ## with &lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    myvar = myvar.replace(/\##(.*?)\##/g, &quot;&lt;span&gt;$1&lt;/span&gt;&quot;);

    // introduce it as a jQuery element
    var $myvar = $(myvar);

    // find &lt;span&gt; in your element and apply styles
    $myvar.find(&#39;span&#39;).css({&#39;color&#39;:&quot;pink&quot;});

    // place it somewhere
    $(&#39;#someDiv&#39;).append($myvar);

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.3.1/jquery.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;div id=someDiv&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

You can take dynamic data in a variable first.

 `var name = ##CandidateName##;
 var email = ##CandidateEmail##;
 var myvar = &#39;&lt;p&gt;Hi, &lt;span&gt;&#39;+name+&#39;&lt;/span&gt; and this is your &lt;span&gt;&#39;+ email 
