answers.body_markdown:
HttpClient is injected out of the box on blazor hosted. On server side you don&#39;t need Rest requests because the backend is in the same place as frond end. Just calling a local function is enough.

Any case, if you need an Http client, for example to go to another site, I suggest to you to use [`IHttpClientFactory`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/fundamentals/http-requests?view=aspnetcore-3.0):

Basic Usage:

1. Add to services: 


        services.AddHttpClient();

2. Get from DI: 


        @inject IHttpClientFactory clientFactory

3. Make request: 


        var client = _clientFactory.CreateClient();

        var response = await client.SendAsync(request);

        if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
        {
            Branches = await response.Content
                .ReadAsAsync&lt;IEnumerable&lt;GitHubBranch&gt;&gt;();
        }
        else
        {
            GetBranchesError = true;
            Branches = Array.Empty&lt;GitHubBranch&gt;();
        }         


This is [Daniel Roth (Blazor product manager) talking about this issue][1]:

&gt;On the server IHttpClientFactory provides a number of benefits for making general HTTP requests that are outlined here: https://docs.microsoft.com/aspnet/core/fundamentals/http-requests.
&gt;
&gt;The HttpClient provided for Blazor WebAssembly Apps is bit more specialized and is specifically configured for making requests back to the server of origin.

Of course, you can also use `HttpClient` adding it to services via DI: 

    services.AddScoped&lt;HttpClient&gt;();



  [1]: https://github.com/aspnet/Blazor/issues/1588#issuecomment-515097675

